In the {{ill|folk beliefs|ja|民間信仰|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Korean Peninsula|ja|朝鮮半島|12=draft}}, "gwi-shin" (귀신) refers to spirits that, unlike ancestral or guardian spirits, do not have a designated host and exist as independent entities.{{Sfn|GWE|2021}}{{Sfn|Soul Worship|2021}} This distinguishes them from spirits that reside within humans or natural elements, such as deities (신명, sinmyeong). However, over time, the distinction between these categories has blurred.{{Sfn|GWE|2021}}{{Sfn|Soul Worship|2021}}
Gwi-shin are depicted as weak and ghostly beings, clad in fragile paper garments, with emaciated legs like glue-covered bones. They are powerless before divine beings and can shrink away when confronted by strong-willed humans.{{Sfn|GWE|2021}} Though typically invisible, they may be appeased with offerings of food. However, some gwi-shin are malevolent and bring misfortune.{{Sfn|GWE|2021}}
During the daytime, gwi-shin wander through the air aimlessly, but at night, they seek damp places to rest.{{Sfn|GWE|2021}} They often reside in ancient trees, shadowy groves, underground spaces, or near wells and ponds. To keep them away, people scatter {{ill|salt|ja|塩|12=draft}} or {{ill|beans|ja|豆|12=draft}}.{{Sfn|GWE|2021}}
Some gwi-shin have supernatural foresight and can predict calamities, warn of impending doom, or reveal the location of lost objects.{{Sfn|GWE|2021}} However, they are generally depicted as being driven away by more powerful entities. In {{ill|Korean folklore|ja|朝鮮の伝説|12=draft}}, figures like {{ill|Cheoyong|ko|처용|12=draft}}, who expelled evil spirits, appear on protective talismans (符籍) to ward off gwi-shin.{{Sfn|GWE|2021}} Additionally, stronger gwi-shin may prey upon weaker ones.{{Sfn|GWE|2021}} It is also believed that even divine spirits can turn into gwi-shin if they lose their place of worship or are forgotten by the living.{{Sfn|GWE|2021}}
