e, and destroy all things in the universe.{{Sfn|Makitani|2021|qq=}} == Korea == {{Korean cultural elements | hangeul = 귀신 | katakana = クィシン|qq=}} In the [[:en:Folk religion|folk beliefs]] of the {{ill|Korean Peninsula|ja|朝鮮半島|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Korean Peninsula|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}, "gwi-shin" (귀신) refers to spirits that, unlike ancestral or guardian spirits, do not have a designated host and exist as independent entities.{{Sfn|GWE|2021|qq=}}{{Sfn|Soul Worship|2021|qq=}} This distinguishes them from spirits that reside within humans or natural elements, such as deities (신명, sinmyeong). However, over time, the distinction between these categories has blurred.{{Sfn|GWE|2021|qq=}}{{Sfn|Soul Worship|2021|qq=}} Gwi-shin are depicted as weak and ghostly beings, clad in fragile paper garments, with emaciated legs like glue-covered bones. They are powerless before divine beings and can shrink away when confronted by strong-willed humans.{{Sfn|GWE|2021|qq=}} Though typically invisible, they may be appeased with offerings of food. However, some gwi-shin are malevolent and bring misfortune.{{Sfn|GWE|2021|qq=}} During the daytime, gwi-shin wander through the air aimlessly, but at night, they seek damp places to rest.{{Sfn|GWE|2021|qq=}} They often reside in ancient trees, shadowy groves, underground spaces, or near wells and ponds. To keep them away, people scatter [[:en:Salt|salt]] or [[:en:Bean|beans]].{{Sfn|GWE|2021|qq=}} Some gwi-shin have supernatural foresight and can predict calamities, warn of impending doom, or reveal the location of lost objects.{{Sfn|GWE|2021|qq=}} However, they are generally depicted as being driven away by more powerful entities. In {{ill|Korean folklore|ja|朝鮮の伝説|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Korean folklore|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, figures like {{ill|Cheoyong|ko|처용|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cheoyong|qq=}}, who expelled evil spirits, appear on protective talismans (符籍) to ward off gwi-shin.{{Sfn|GWE|2021|qq=}} Additionally, stronger gwi-shin may prey upon weaker ones.{{Sfn|GWE|2021|qq=}} It is also believed that even divine spirits can turn into gwi-shin if they lose their place of worship or are forgotten by the living.{{Sfn|GWE|2021|qq=}} == References == {{reflist|qq=}} == Bibliography == * {{Cite book|title=Global World Encyclopedia|publisher=Doosan Corporation|qq=}} * {{Cite web|url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E9%AC%BC%E7%A5%9E-50543#E7.B2.BE.E9.81.B8.E7.89.88.20.E6.97.A5.E6.9C.AC.E5.9B.BD.E8.AA.9E.E5.A4.A7.E8.BE.9E.E5.85.B8 |title=鬼神 |publisher=Shogakukan |work=Nihon Kokugo Daijiten |date=2021-07-16 |language=ja|qq=}} * {{Cite web|url=https://ko.wikisource.org/wiki/%EA%B8%80%EB%A1%9C%EB%B2%8C_%EC%84%B8%EA%B3%84_%EB%8C%80%EB%B0%B1%EA%B3%BC%EC%82%AC%EC%A0%84/%EC%A2%85%EA%B5%90%C2%B7%EC%B2%A0%ED%95%99/%ED%95%9C%EA%B5%AD%EC%9D%98_%EC%A2%85%EA%B5%90/%EB%AF%BC_%EA%B0%84_%EC%8B%A0_%EC%95%99/%EC%88%AD_%EB%B0%B0#%EA%B7%80%EC%8B%A0 |title=귀신 (鬼神) |publisher=Global World Encyclopedia |date=2021-07-16 |language=ko|qq=}} == See Also == * [[:en:Arai Hakuseki|Arai Hakuseki]]'s *{{ill|On Kishin|ja|鬼神論|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/On Kishin|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}* * [[:en:Yamagata Bantō|Yamakata Bantō]]'s *{{ill|Yume no Shiro|ja|夢の代|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yume no Shiro|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}* * [[:en:Hirata Atsutane|Hirata Atsutane]]'s *{{ill|Kishin Shinron|ja|鬼神新論|qq=|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishin Shinron|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}*
